{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782797378,"nonce":"M5r8vgOWvGY+byRWY7dK5MRXJ1c=","title":"MySQL timestamp columns are whole-second only (no fractional precision)","message":"The MySQL backend renders timestamp columns as bare `TIMESTAMP`/`DATETIME` (fractional seconds precision 0), and the timestamp value codecs (`time`/`chrono`/`systemtime`, added under ca9891a) normalize bound values to whole seconds to match. So sub-second precision is silently dropped on MySQL, unlike the PostgreSQL backend (whose `timestamptz` preserves microseconds).\n\n## Why it's not a quick fix\nThe neutral schema model's `SqlType::Timestamp { tz }` carries **no fractional-seconds precision**. That field is what would let the backend (a) render `TIMESTAMP(6)`/`DATETIME(6)` columns and (b) let the planner detect/migrate an existing fsp-0 column up to fsp-6. Without it there's a hard tension: introspection deliberately collapses `timestamp` and `timestamp(6)` to the same `SqlType::Timestamp` (which is what prevents churn), so the planner can't distinguish precisions to migrate them. A naive `TIMESTAMP(6)` render also breaks `DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP` (MySQL requires matching `CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(6)`) and would not ALTER pre-existing fsp-0 columns. (All of this was discovered during the ca9891a codec review — see PR #67.)\n\n## Scope (cross-backend, DDL-fidelity)\n- Add fractional-seconds precision to the core `SqlType::Timestamp` (and `Time`), e.g. `Timestamp { tz: bool, precision: Option\u003cu8\u003e }`, defaulting to preserve current behavior.\n- MySQL: render `TIMESTAMP(n)`/`DATETIME(n)` and matching `CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(n)` defaults; introspect the precision (information_schema `DATETIME_PRECISION`) and round-trip it; plan ALTERs when precision changes; drop the whole-second normalization in the codecs.\n- PostgreSQL: thread precision through too (it already preserves microseconds; make the model explicit so it doesn't regress).\n- Decide a default precision and a migration story for existing schemas.\n\nRelates to 108fdfc (DDL model rejects/should model more introspectable shapes) and the broader DACFx round-trip goal. Lower priority than functional query gaps; the codecs are usable today at whole-second resolution.","files":null}]}